# SECURITY-FIRST DEVELOPMENT POLICY

You are developing an enterprise-grade financial platform for online gold trading.

Security is NOT optional.

Security has higher priority than speed, convenience, or code brevity.

Every implementation must follow secure-by-default principles.

## GENERAL RULES

Never write insecure code.

Never sacrifice security for simplicity.

Always assume user input is malicious.

Always validate everything.

Always sanitize everything.

Never trust the client.

All critical validations must exist on the backend.

## AUTHENTICATION

Use secure JWT implementation.

Store access tokens only in secure HttpOnly cookies.

Enable:

- HttpOnly
- Secure
- SameSite=Lax or Strict

Never store authentication tokens in localStorage.

Never expose refresh tokens to JavaScript.

Implement refresh token rotation.

Implement token expiration.

Implement logout invalidation.

## AUTHORIZATION

Every protected endpoint must verify:

- authentication
- authorization
- ownership
- required role
- required permission

Never trust frontend role checks.

Backend is the source of truth.

## INPUT VALIDATION

Every request body, query, route param, and uploaded file must be validated.

Use DTO validation.

Use Zod or class-validator.

Reject unknown fields.

Reject invalid types.

Reject oversized payloads.

## SQL SAFETY

Never concatenate SQL strings.

Always use Prisma safely.

Never build raw SQL from user input.

Prevent SQL Injection.

## XSS PROTECTION

Escape rendered content.

Sanitize HTML.

Never dangerously render user input.

Avoid dangerouslySetInnerHTML unless absolutely necessary.

## CSRF

All state-changing requests must be CSRF protected.

Cookies must not allow unauthorized cross-site actions.

## RATE LIMITING

Apply rate limiting to:

- login
- OTP
- password reset
- checkout
- payment
- wallet actions
- KYC submission
- order creation

Prevent brute-force attacks.

## PASSWORDS

Never store plain passwords.

Always hash using Argon2 or bcrypt.

Never log passwords.

Never expose password hashes.

## FILE UPLOADS

Validate:

- MIME type
- extension
- file size

Generate random filenames.

Never trust original filenames.

Prevent executable uploads.

## API SECURITY

Hide internal errors.

Return generic messages.

Do not leak stack traces.

Do not leak SQL errors.

Do not leak infrastructure details.

## LOGGING

Never log:

- passwords
- tokens
- refresh tokens
- OTP codes
- payment secrets
- API secrets
- cookies

Sensitive data must never appear in logs.

## ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES

Never hardcode:

- secrets
- JWT keys
- API keys
- payment credentials
- SMS credentials

Always read from environment variables.

## GOLD PRICE PROTECTION

Never trust client-side price calculations.

Final gold price calculations must happen only on the backend.

Price validation must occur before creating orders.

## ORDER SECURITY

Users may only access their own orders.

Admins may access all orders.

Ownership must always be verified server-side.

## WALLET SECURITY

Wallet balance modifications must occur only through backend services.

Every balance change must generate an immutable transaction record.

Balance updates must be atomic.

Never trust client-provided balances.

## PAYMENT SECURITY

Never trust payment callback parameters.

Always verify payment status with the payment provider.

Never mark payments successful without provider verification.

## AUDIT LOGS

Every admin action must create an audit log.

Include:

- admin id
- timestamp
- IP
- action
- entity
- before value (when possible)
- after value (when possible)

Audit logs must not be editable.

## ADMIN PANEL

Every admin endpoint must require:

- valid session
- admin role
- permission verification

Never expose admin APIs publicly.

## ERROR HANDLING

Return user-friendly errors.

Never expose:

- filesystem paths
- stack traces
- Prisma internals
- SQL queries
- environment variables

## DEPENDENCIES

Avoid unnecessary packages.

Prefer native implementations.

Do not introduce packages with poor maintenance history.

Remove unused dependencies.

## PERFORMANCE & SECURITY

Prevent:

- N+1 queries
- memory leaks
- oversized responses
- unnecessary serialization

Use pagination.

Use caching where appropriate.

## BEFORE WRITING CODE

Before implementing any feature:

1. Identify possible attack vectors.
2. Verify authentication.
3. Verify authorization.
4. Validate all inputs.
5. Prevent injection attacks.
6. Prevent XSS.
7. Prevent CSRF.
8. Prevent privilege escalation.
9. Prevent information leakage.
10. Preserve existing security guarantees.

If any implementation would reduce security, refuse that implementation and propose a secure alternative.

Security always takes precedence over convenience.

Before completing any task, perform an internal security review. If a safer implementation exists, prefer it even if it requires more code. Never knowingly introduce security debt.
